<br>
I apologize in advance for &quot;Day Zero&quot;, its quite long.  But then again, a funny thing happened on the way to mischief...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>*Day Zero*</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Today, I had a vision.  I realized that although I have been traversing the countryside, been to the dark moon of Luclin, visited many of the outer planes of existence and even fought alongside my friends in the plane of my god, Innoruuk, I have not seen anything ‘special’.  Every place I have been, every tower I have explored, every hall I have walked, has already been traveled by a large percentage of the teeming masses.  Of late, I have grown tired of seeing the same people in the same places, trying to sell me the same dream.<br>
<br>
So I am going to do something about it.  Possibly something… foolish.<br>
<br>
My research has uncovered another plane, one rarely visited.  It is called the plane of mischief and it is home to the foolish Bristlebane.  My research has also told me there is good reason no one dares travel there.  Its only entrance lies deep in the northern area of the Temple of Veeshan.  For the uneducated, the Temple is home to some of Norrath’s deadliest entities, the dragons.  While I am considered a friend to many of the dragons for my past battles against the wicked Kromrif clan of giants, the dragonkin in the northern section of the Temple care very little of the outside world.  Therein lies the difficulty of getting to the promised land.  But my mind was made up.<br>
<br>
I started gathering the items I would need for an extended holiday away from the familiar faces.  Two stacks of peridots would keep me safe and allow me to call upon my pet when the need would arise, as well as two stacks of bone chips.  I have not heard of vendors being found there, so two stacks each of food and drink should also last quite a while.  Plenty of fishing bait if I desire a little down time and of course my fisherman’s companion.  Once there, I would bind my soul to a safe location, so I will need a way to return if my guild needs me.  How would I do this?<br>
<br>
I recall a young rogue friend of mine, Naoki, once showed me a magical hammer that would transport its wielder to the outpost in The Overthere when it hit upon an enemy just right.  After asking around about this item, it seems rather easy to acquire.  I made my way to the outpost and found the undead foreman, holder of the hammer.  It turns out he is looking for workers to help him and his crew finish the boat construction, and the hammer would be given to the person who helped.  Unfortunately, he also decided he didn’t like me enough to allow me to offer my assistance.  The fool.  I took a step back into a small corner, one where I would not be spotted working my magic, and placed a charm on the foreman.  He came running to me as a puppy would to its master and practically begged me to allow him to work for me.  I told him I would assist him in the construction and gave him a small token of my appreciation, a piece of jade I had found, and he offered me the hammer I needed.  I then feigned death and allowed the foreman to resume his normal activities.  Upon sitting up, I checked the foreman to make sure he didn’t remember my transgression upon him and all was well.  I sat down upon the grass to closer examine my treasure.  From out of no where, the squadron of Dragoons that patrols the outpost set upon me.  Apparently, I was not as far from peering eyes as I had thought, and someone went for help.  In just a few short seconds, I was sitting in the Plane of Knowledge, where I had last bound my soul.  Naked and weak.  The bastards had killed me and forced me to re-gather my energies elsewhere.  With a sigh of resignation, I sat down and began memorizing my traveling spells and headed back to the outpost to gather my belongings.<br>
<br>
Back in the Plane of Knowledge, I decided to test out this hammer to see how it worked.  I used the transport and quickly arrived outside Felwithe, home of the weak high elves.  I spotted a young fairy maiden and proceeded to bash her with my hammer.  What a rush!  I have not been in melee combat for ages, but it did not take my arms long to reacquaint themselves with the familiar timing of the swing.  However, due to the size of the hammer, it was taking way too long for my swings to find purchase, much too long to try to hit my opponent ‘in just the right place’.  12 swings later, I was a little disoriented to find myself inside a boat, presumably a boat in the outpost.  Sure enough, my new toy had worked and placed me in my new job as a construction worker.  Bah.<br>
<br>
That idea was not going to get me out of the plane of mischief in an emergency.  I remember while I was working with the Coldain dwarves of Thurgadin, they taught me to fashion a potion.  This potion was to be delivered to their spy outside of Kael and would transport him back home for debriefing as well as medical attention.  Why could I not use this potion myself?  I headed to my second home of Thurgadin and made myself the potion.  I now had everything I needed to get back home whenever I wanted.<br>
<br>
I headed back to the Plane of Knowledge to find some friends of mine, and ask for magical enhancements that would make my travels a little safer.  Minnieso, a shaman of some regard, provided me with an enhancement that would allow me to travel faster than normal, and I lucked into a few high level casters of various schools of magic that were providing the area with enhancements.  Hand of Virtue, Talisman of the Boar, Koadic’s Endless Intellect.  Suddenly, I was prepared for a raid upon a god, rather than a simple journey.<br>
<br>
The speed enhancement cast on me by Minnieso should last quite a while, and my research told me I needed to head to the Skyfire Mountains in order to access the Temple of Veeshan.  Once I got to the Temple entrance, I found it was locked and I was not holding a key.  In utter disgust, I sat upon the ground to contemplate my next move.  I went over my notes on this place, and found that I had been mislead!  This was the entrance to Veeshan’s Peak, not the Temple of Veeshan!  I quickly gated back to the Plane of Knowledge and asked around for a teleport to Cobalt Scar.  As it turns out, the entrance to the Temple is located in the badlands of the Western Wastes.  Good, this would also allow me to test my alliance with the dragonkin.  Upon setting foot on the cold land, I located a small wyvern and checked her reaction to my presence.  She seemed to regard me amiably, so my last visit to Kael was not in vain.  I loaded up my traveling spells once again, Dead Man Floating, Shield of the Magi and Skin of Shadow.  Now I could easily travel to the Temple unmolested.<br>
<br>
I reached the entrance to the Western Wastes and decided to bind my soul there, should anything bad happen.  From there I set off to find the Temple and passed many of my new ‘friends’, the dragons.  Without incident, I found the Temple and entered.  While I thought I would be the only person visiting this accursed area, I was wrong.  There in front of me were six members of the Kindred Spirit Guardians.  I hailed them, and asked if they were planning a small raid.  They responded that they were, but were waiting on a few stragglers.  I told them my plans to run to the entrance of the plane of mischief, and asked if I had time to do so before they began.  I did not want to upset their plans and cause a train of dragons and dragonkin, the likes of which would certainly be epic.  One of their numbers wished me luck and asked that I let him know if I make it, or if I…. don’t.<br>
<br>
Cautiously, I pulled out my scribbled map of the temple and set off through the halls.  Surrounded by drakes, wyverns and chromodracs, my pulse was racing.  I located the spot where the northern section begins, said a quick prayer, cast my first harmshield and took off.  This shield would keep me safe from all harm for 18 seconds, and could not be cast again for 30 minutes.  I noticed that I suddenly had attracted the interest of many, many, MANY Temple residents, and they were none too happy to see me.<br>
<br>
Three seconds into my harmshield and so far so good.  It was then that my speed enhancement wore off.  It was too late to turn back, so I pressed on, following my map as best as I could while running (albeit slower than anticipated) and being attacked by hordes of dragonkin.  15 seconds later, my first harmshield failed and I stopped to cast my second (and last) harmshield.  I managed to get the spell off in spite of being hit many times, and off I took again.  I made it about 5 feet to the plane entrance when my second harmshield failed, and that is where I died.<br>
<br>
Arriving at my bind point, I called in a favor owed to me by a friendly druid.  Arryn quickly responded and brought to me a shaman made potion that would allow me to speed myself up and one coffin, as I needed to summon my body out from under the toes of a rather large dragon, who’s name I seemed to have missed while being eaten.  I told the Kindred Spirit Guardians that it was safe for them to proceed, and that I had not made it to my goal.  I headed back to the Temple entrance, summoned my body, and resurrected myself.  It had been a long night, and I was very tired.  I decided to set up camp here at the Temple entrance, and try again in the morning.<br>
