<br>
*Stretch*<br>
<br>
*Yawn*<br>
<br>
I must admit, the temperature in this area is very conducive to a good night’s sleep.  Aside from the dragon roar at about midnight, I slept like the dead.  As a matter of fact, I am so rested and relaxed, now would be the perfect time to make another attempt to enter the plane of mischief.<br>
<br>
I take a step outside and use my shaman speed potion, as well as casting all my defensive and traveling spells.  Once back in this godforsaken Temple, I take out my map to examine my path for the last time.  Committed to memory, I take off through the halls.  There seems to be more residents around that during my last terrifying run, although none of them look unique.  Mostly drakes and wyverns.  Once I hit the area in the northern section where my invisibility spell no longer cloaks me from my enemy’s vision, I cast my first harmshield, say a quick prayer to Innoruuk and take off across the cliff as fast as I can.  Soon, I am once again surrounded by the flapping of wings and various curses, while claws and magic attempt to rend my body to pieces.  I make it about half way to the entrance, and pause for a moment to cast my second harmshield.  If this shield will hold out long enough, and if I am able to find the entrance, I should be fine.  Mid-cast, however, I notice a wisp of smoke coming from my arm.  Then the pain starts, and I am barely able to continue my casting.  I summon all my strength to fight the pain and manage to get my shield spell off.  No time to think, I must continue running.  Up the cliff, across its apex and down a small hill, I look ahead to see a hall way leading to the right.  Standing in the entrance of this hall is a rather large wurm.  If memory serves me correctly, this is the wurm which killed me yesterday, so that means I am close.  I begin to feel the shield keeping me alive start to wane, so I make haste past the wurm and down the hall.  My informants tell me, just down the hall here is a small tile on the floor, in the shape of a castle.  One touch to this tile is all I need to teleport me to the plane of mischief.  I frantically search the ground for this tile, but am unable to see it.  I pause for a moment to look around, and the area is suddenly filled with multi-colored claws scraping against the floor.  I feel a singe of fire against my skin and realize my shielding is gone… and that is when I see the tile I am looking for.  Five feet away, I make a desperate lunge for the ground.  Just as my fingers touch the smooth surface, I feel the sting of a claw pierce my leg, and I am plunged into darkness.<br>
<br>
I materialize upon a blue platform in the middle of a forest.  This, however, is unlike any forest I have ever been in.  The trees are topped with pink and golden leaves, the air is heavy and there is an odd smell that I cannot name.  In the distance, I spot what looks like a denizen of this area.  Vaguely, it reminds me of the Moldmaster found in the deep mines of Runnyeye, but a darker green.  A large bixie flies towards me, glances in my direction and keeps on its course.  Good, it would appear that nothing in the immediate area seems to care about my presence.  Quite a nice change.  And that smell again… familiar and yet unrecognizable.<br>
<br>
So enraptured by my new surroundings, I fail to realize that I am wounded.  Suddenly, I put a name to the smell, rotting flesh.  I look down at my arm and notice there is an infection that is eating away at my skin, rapidly.  Thinking back to the recent past, I recall my arm being hit with a fluid while casting my second shield in the Temple.  While I watch, the infection spreads down my arm and onto my hand.  My strength is beginning to fail, and I am slipping into unconsciousness.  Faster than I have ever moved before, I rip my spell book from my robes and quickly look up my soul binding spell.  I memorize that spell, and while I gather my energies to cast it, begin to memorize my strongest lifetap.  I stand to bind my soul, my legs buckle and I stutter a word.  The seriousness of this situation begins to gnaw at my soul.  I will die very soon, if I cannot cast this spell, I will re-gather my energies at the entrance to the Temple of Veeshan.  And all of my equipment will be here, in the plane of mischief.  I calm my mind and begin casting again.  A wave of relief washes over me as I can feel my essence attune to my surroundings.  Moments left before I fade into darkness, I quickly rummage through my pouches in search of my salvation.  My fingers close upon a stalking probe, made for me by my good gnomish friend, Vegann.  Fumbling with the object, I find its activation button and watch as it unfolds into an eye.  I cast my lifetap on the eye and sit down to let the healing begin.  As I suspected, dragons have very strong magic, and even stronger spit!  All told, it took five lifetaps from my, now useless, stalking probe to fully combat the effects of the vile substance.<br>
<br>
With the desperation fading, I can now begin to make plans to explore this new area.  I summon forth my spectre companion and move hesitantly into the forest.  As I approach, nothing seems to be aware of my presence.  I keep moving along the edge of the plane, when I feel a light tap against my back and my minion is telling me it is attacking my aggressor.  Spinning around, I come face-to-face with… a grumpy tree?  How odd.  And this tree is throwing pansies at me!  And these pansies are fighting my pet (and winning).  I gather my energies and begin to heal my pet and cast my most aggressive damage over time spells on these flowers.  I root them to the ground and ask my pet to kindly back away from the pansies.  They remind me of the aggressive flowers in the Emerald Jungle, but much stronger.  After what seems like an eternity, I am victorious against the flora and stoop to examine my slain enemy.  Tangled in its roots is what appears to be a fishing grub.  But this grub is sweet smelling and a little larger than the ones found on the ground around Norrath.<br>
<br>
Pressing on through the forest, I come upon a moat surrounding a castle.  This must be the home of Bristlebane, god of mischief.  I follow the moat and find a bridge leading to a rampart, where a rather large hand is crawling across.  Following this large hand, is a smaller hand.  Listening to their conversation, it would seem the large hand is called ‘My Finger’ and the smaller, ‘Not Yours’.  Very curious, the residents of this plane.  I move to take a step onto the bridge and find myself plunged in the moat.  Bah! An illusion!  I drag myself out of the moat only to find a young female Halfling running by with a large bixie following closely behind.  The Halfling glances over her shoulder at the bixie and excitedly asks if they can play in the water of the moat.  The bixie does not seem very interested, and wanders off, soon followed by the Halfling.  I follow the moat to its end to a waterfall.  Across the moat on the rampart is another Halfling, male this time, fishing.  I cast Dead Man Floating upon myself and make my way towards the rampart wall.  My foot catches on something mid air and I realize there is an invisible bridge leading to the top.  I run up the bridge and cautiously approach the Halfling.  He resembles the sheriffs of Rivervale but does not seem to share their disdain of dark elves.  Although he does not attack me out-right, I recall hearing from a friend not to talk to the residents of this plane, until I know a little more about them.  Leaving the Halfling alone, I travel along the rampart to the false bridge, passing both hands as I go.  The moat continues along both sides of the wall, and across the moat is the castle.<br>
<br>
Before me is a bridge leading across the moat to the castle entrance, complete with 2 or 3 arches.  Hoping this is not another illusion, I start to cross the bridge.  I make it to the other side of the bridge when I hear a strange chanting coming from the arch!  I turn around to see what is happening and suddenly I am stripped of all my enchantments.  Cursing under my breath, I sit down to memorize my defense spells again.  I stand and begin casting my personal shield.  Poof, dispelled again.  I move into the castle courtyard and cast my shield again. It sticks!  I finish my defense routine and move further into the castle.  Guarding the door are two skunks.  Past the skunks is another door, which will not open.  It is not locked, it is not magically sealed… then I realize the door is a ruse.  I search the area for a secret entrance and come upon a hall, hidden by an illusion of a wall at its front.  I make my way down the hall and through several corridors when I finally come upon a room.  In the center of this room, on a small platform, is a large treasure chest.  There are three halls leading off this room one across from me, and one on my left and right.  The walls of are covered with paintings, but all the paintings are the same.  The face of Bristlebane himself.  I approach the chest to inspect it and realize it is a living being.  I step back, augment my pet, and send it in to attack.  It has been much too long since my last slaughter, and I am eager to see what the spoils of battle will be here.  Upon its first hit, my pet is set upon by no less than four guards, all of whom materialized from the corners of the room.  I know this is no battle I can win, so I feign death and let my pet get slaughtered.  When the dust of the quick battle settles, I stand and ponder this new development.  Now I know, while a room may look safe at first glance,  don’t expect it to remain so during a fight.<br>
<br>
Tired from processing all of this new information, I decide to bind my soul here at this location, and set up camp for the evening. In the Plane of Mischief. Alone and far away from my friends...<br>
